<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0160</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Mendip Bridleways &amp; Byways Association – Written evidence</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Mendip Bridleways &amp; Byways Association covers the 69 Parishes in Mendip, Somerset.  We are an entirely voluntary organisation which raises funds by running a variety of events throughout the year, all of which are used to improve and create riding routes for all users.  We have over 400 members and we work very hard to achieve our aims.  Over the past years we have experienced considerable delays and obstacles when submitting DMMOs to Somerset County Council so are very pleased to welcome the findings of the Stakeholder Working Group and their Stepping Forward Report.  However despite these new guidelines, we are still frustrated by the very restrictive structure within which we are forced to work in order to achieve our aims through SCC (Somerset County Council)  There is a huge backlog of DMMOs at SCC and there are unreasonable delays on the scoring of DMMOs -  many routes will not be considered for almost thirty years which must surely  be a disgrace and hardly seen as ‘progress’.  Could the whole process not be considerably simplified?  Perhaps this massive backlog could be ‘loaned out’ to other Councils who have the man power and capability of processing DMMOs promptly in order to bring the Rights of Way in Somerset in line with the rest of the country?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Unfortunately there is no magic pot of gold held by user groups who wish to submit DMMOs;  most  are hard-pressed voluntary organisations working for the good of the neighbourhood and the bigger society.   In many cases the time and costs involved in preparing and presenting an Order are as much as any association can handle.  Despite being in a better financial situation than many, MBBA uses its funds to best effect by paying contractors to improve routes in Mendip and there is insufficient money to pay for expensive appeals on DMMOs.  To this end, MBBA agrees that landowners will be less defensive if approached by their local council in the first instance, at which point sensible negotiations for an acceptable route could be agreed, well in advance of a DMMO being submitted.  Importantly, this should avoid lengthy confrontation and the necessity for an appeal and extra expense.   </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Great care and thought needs to be taken in raising any threshold in which an Authority must make an order as this must surely involve an added and unwanted cost for the applicant.  Presumably, using a Magistrate’s Court in order to chase up Councils for their failure to process DMMos  is once again beyond the funds of the majority of Associations.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The vital task of saving our historic Rights of Way is being left to voluntary groups across the country.   These groups need to be 100% confident of the support and co-operation of their Councils </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in order to achieve this huge task, the success of which will benefit the economy and well-being of Great Britain for many years to come.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>